{{nihongo|'''Katsunari Takayama'''|高山 勝成|Takayama Katsunari|extra=born May 12, 1983 in [[Osaka]], [[Osaka Prefecture]]}} is a Japanese professional [[Boxing|boxer]] who is the current [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] [[Minimumweight|mini flyweight]] champion. He is the former [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] minimumweight [[Interim championship|interim champion]], and the former [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] minimumweight champion. Currently he trains at his fellow boxer Ken'ichi Yamaguchi's Osaka Tenjin Boxing Gym in Japan{{Sfn|Fitness Sports|2012|p=78}} and ALA Boxing Gym in the [[Philippines]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/sports/view/20100429-267089/Japanese-ex-world-champ-trains-at-ALA-gym|title=Japanese ex-world champ trains at ALA gym|author=Salven Lagumbay, Rene Bonsubre Jr. (''Cebu Daily News'')|date=April 29, 2010|publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer|Inquirer.net]]|accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref> and is promoted by ALA Promotions since April 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/sports/view/20100429-267088/Aldeguer-After-25-years-ALA-Promotions-set-to-go-global|title=Aldeguer: After 25 years ALA Promotions set to go global|author=Salven Lagumbay (''Cebu Daily News'')|date=April 29, 2010|publisher=Inquirer.net|accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref> While Takayama has gone through four gyms,<ref name="jōjima200504" /><ref name="asazawa2007">{{Harvnb|Asazawa|Shibuya|2007|p=61}}</ref> his Japanese trainer for his entire career is Hiroaki Nakade<ref name="jōjima200504" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.15rounds.com/q-a-with-katsunari-takayama-062910/|title=Q & A with Katsunari Takayama|author=Anson Wainwright|date=June 29, 2010|publisher=15rounds.com|accessdate=February 18, 2013}}</ref> who has so far served as the second/trainer in the world title bouts of all the four major sanctioning bodies i.e. WBA, WBC, [[International Boxing Federation|IBF]] (for Takayama fights) and [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]] (for [[Orlando Salido]] vs. Yamaguchi).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boxingnewsboxon.blogspot.jp/2011/07/11_24.html|title=山口11回TKO負け　WBOフェザー級戦＝詳報|author=''Boxing Beat'' editorial department|date=July 24, 2011|publisher=MACC Publications Inc|language=Japanese|accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref>

== Biography and career ==
=== In Japan ===
Takayama weighed about 60&nbsp;kg at the age of twelve. He started playing rugby and athletics, but did not last long. It was in summer in the second grade of junior high school that his friend brought him to a boxing gym. When he got started on the punching bag, despite he said he is going to be a world champion, he could not do more than three push-ups in a row. Even after his own workout, he had been watching senior boxers' sparring sessions and trainees' training without getting bored at the entrance of the gym. Takayama made his professional debut in October 2000 and won the All-Japan Rookie King Tournament in December 2001.<ref name="jōjima200504" />

==== WBC title ====
On April 4, 2005 Takayama defeated [[Isaac Bustos]] for the [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] world title, by a unanimous decision. This victory gave Takayama the distinction of being the 50th Japanese fighter to win a world title.
However, he lost a next bout against [[Eagle Kyowa]] by a unanimous decision, on August 6, 2005.

==== Interim WBA title ====
On November 7, 2006 he defeated [[Carlos Melo]] for the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[interim title]] when he was originally supposed to face [[Yutaka Niida]] for the WBA title in September. However, due to a costal cartilage fracture<ref>{{Harvnb|Asazawa|Shibuya|2007|p=21}}</ref> Niida sustained from sparring, the fight would be delayed to April 7, 2007 ending in a split decision loss. After the fight, his then manager rejected the decision and uttered that it was a [[match fixing]] and that he would make civil litigation. However, he visited the JBC (Japan Boxing Commission) two days later and apologized for his rant saying that he had just wanted to pat his boxer on the back.<ref>{{Cite news|title=高山勝成陣営、強硬姿勢から一転謝罪|url=http://www.nikkansports.com/battle/f-bt-tp0-20070409-182264.html|publisher=''[[Nikkan Sports]]''|date=April 9, 2007|accessdate=March 31, 2012|language=Japanese|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20070503162351/http://www.nikkansports.com/battle/f-bt-tp0-20070409-182264.html|archivedate=May 3, 2007}}</ref> Furthermore, most of the purse for that fight had not been paid. Although Takayama and Nakade announced that they would transfer to any other gym, the matters on the match fee and transfer fee were not resolved over months.<ref name="asazawa2007" />

Takayama got another world title shot on July 14, 2009. This time, it was for the WBA minimumweight title which is held by [[Román González (boxer)|Roman Gonzalez]]. Unsuccessfully, Takayama lost on all judges. He retired as a JBC-licenced boxer to fight for the WBO and IBF's titles in late 2009.{{Sfn|Fitness Sports|2012|p=78}}  At that time the JBC had approved no fight for the WBO and IBF's titles, but conditionally allowed them from February 28, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jbc.or.jp/rls/2011/0309.html|title=委員長会議報告書|date=March 9, 2011|publisher=Japan Boxing Commission|language=Japanese|accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref> That is because the West Japan Boxing Association to which Takayama and Ken'ichi Yamaguchi belonged strongly urged reform of the system after they issued retirement notices.{{Sfn|Fitness Sports|2012|p=78}}<ref>{{Cite news|title=WBOとIBFへの加盟申し入れ|url=http://www.daily.co.jp/ring/2010/10/16/0003535758.shtml|publisher=''[[Kobe Shimbun|Daily Sports]]''|date=October 15, 2010|accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref>

=== Away from Japan ===
Takayama won an IBF minimumweight title eliminator via a sixth round technical knockout at the Carnival City in [[Brakpan]], [[Gauteng]], [[South Africa]] in September 2010,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/cebudailynews/sports/view/20100903-290280/Takayama-stops-Lefele-in-6th-round-of-their-IBF-eliminator|title=Takayama stops Lefele in 6th round of their IBF eliminator|author=Rene Bonsubre Jr. (''Cebu Daily News'')|date=September 3, 2010|publisher=Inquirer.net|accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref> and challenged [[Nkosinathi Joyi]] for that title at the Carnival City after being postponed twice<ref>{{Cite news|title=2度延期もプラス…高山、南アへ「KOで倒したい」|url=http://www.sponichi.co.jp/battle/news/2011/01/24/kiji/K20110124000110090.html|publisher=''[[Sports Nippon]]''|date=January 24, 2011|accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref> on January 29, 2011, but the fight ended in a no-contest due to a cut on Takayama's head after an accidental head-butt in the third round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&opt=printable&id=35329|title=Joyi-Takayama a No-Contest, Mendez Decisions Baloyi|author=Chris LaBate|date=January 29, 2011|publisher=BoxingScene.com|accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref> He had a broken right hand since just before the fight.{{Sfn|Fitness Sports|2012|p=78}} 

Takayama rematched Joyi at the Orient Theatre in [[East London, Eastern Cape]] after postponed four times{{Sfn|Fitness Sports|2012|p=78}} on March 30, 2012. It was the [[South African Broadcasting Corporation|SABC]]-televised second boxing event after one year interruption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ringtv.craveonline.com/blog/172147-joyi-finally-getting-tv-time-against-takayama|title=Joyi finally getting TV time against Takayama|author=Corey Erdman|date=March 29, 2012|publisher=[[The Ring (magazine)|RingTV]]|accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref> According to Japanese sources, Takayama reportedly dominated the whole fight except that he went down resulting from a slip in the fifth round,<ref>{{Cite news|title=高山、敵地で0–3判定負け…IBF世界ミニマム級|url=http://hochi.yomiuri.co.jp/osaka/sports/article/news/20120401-OHO1T00116.htm|publisher=''[[Sports Hochi]]'' (Osaka Edition)|date=April 1, 2012|accessdate=April 3, 2012|language=Japanese}}</ref> and stated with increased confidence through the twelve rounds that "I fought as was planned and did my best"<ref>{{Cite news|title=高山勝成、新王者ならず…地元判定に泣く|url=http://www.daily.co.jp/newsflash/2012/03/31/0004930888.shtml|publisher=''Daily Sports''|date=March 31, 2012|accessdate=March 31, 2012|language=Japanese}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=高山、判定で敗れる　IBFミニマム級|author=[[Kyodo News]]|url=http://www.nikkei.com/sports/news/article/g=96958A9C81818A9995E2E2E6EB8DE1E3E2E1E0E2E3E0E2E2E2E2E2E2;da=96958A88889DE2E0E3EAEAE5E6E2E0E3E3E0E0E2E2EBE2E2E2E2E2E2|publisher=''[[Nihon Keizai Shimbun]]''|date=March 31, 2012|accessdate=March 31, 2012|language=Japanese}}</ref> after a unanimous decision loss with scores of 111–116 twice and 110–117.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&opt=printable&id=51228|title=Nkosinathi Joyi Decisions Katsunari Takayama To Retain|author=Alexey Sukachev|date=March 30, 2012|publisher=BoxingScene.com|accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref> A boxing writer for South Africa's [[SuperSport (TV channel)|SuperSport]] wrote that "Many ringsiders were of the opinion that the decision could have gone in favour of the challenger" on Fightnews.com<ref name="ronjackson201203">{{Cite web|url=http://www.fightnews.com/Boxing/joyi-retains-ibf-minimumweight-belt-111692|title=Joyi retains IBF minimumweight belt|author=Ron Jackson|date=March 31, 2012|publisher=Fightnews.com|accessdate=March 31, 2012}}</ref> which was presented the WBA’s Website of the Year in 2010,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fightnews.com/Boxing/wba-2010-awards-banquet-67945|title=WBA 2010 Awards Banquet|author=Boxing Bob Newman|date=November 24, 2010|publisher=Fightnews.com|accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref> and there were several articles showing that Joyi had struggled against Takayama.<ref name="ronjackson201203" /> However the IBF's Lindsey Tucker has denied their views on BoxingScene.com.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&opt=printable&id=51323|title=IBF Responds To Allegations of Takayama Being Robbed|author=Ronnie Nathanielsz|date=April 2, 2012|publisher=BoxingScene.com|accessdate=April 3, 2012}}</ref>

He fought against Filipino Mateo Handig for the vacant IBF Pan Pacific mini flyweight title and the mandatory challenger status to the IBF mini flyweight title in [[La Trinidad, Benguet]], Philippines on October 13, 2012. But he lost the fight via a split decision after being deducted a point in the fourth round for pushing. Two Filipino judges scored the fight 114&ndash;113 for Handig, while the other Thai judge scored it 115&ndash;112 for Takayama.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cebu/sports/2012/10/15/handig-pulls-stunning-upset-over-takayama-248054|title=Handig pulls off stunning upset over Takayama|author=Edri K. Aznar|date=October 15, 2012|publisher=''[[Sun.Star Cebu]]''|accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fightnews.com/Boxing/handig-singwangcha-decisions-takayama-142010|title=Handig Singwangcha decisions Takayama|author=Chito Yu Katangkatang|date=October13, 2012|publisher=Fightnews.com|accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref> The IBF ordered a rematch due to the inadequacy of the mandatory [[Doping in sport|drug testing]] before and after the fight.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Roderick Osis|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/baguio/sports/2013/01/19/ibf-orders-handig-takayama-rematch-263643|title=IBF orders Handig–Takayama rematch|publisher=''[[Sun.Star]]''|date=January 19, 2012|accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref> After Handig's injury, Takayama earned the right to challenge for the world title.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jiji.com/jc/c?g=spo_30&k=2013022100942|title=高山のタイトル戦決定＝3度目の挑戦、メキシコで－IBFミニマム級|publisher=[[Jiji Press]]|date=February 21, 2013|accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref>

==== IBF title ====
Takayama defeated [[Mario Rodriguez (boxer)|Mario Rodríguez]] via a unanimous decision with the scores of 119&ndash;109, 117&ndash;111 and 115&ndash;113 to be crowned the IBF mini flyweight world champion at the [[Estadio Francisco Carranza Limón]] in [[Guasave, Sinaloa]], [[Mexico]] on March 30, 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://deportes.terra.cl/otros-deportes/japones-takayama-vence-a-mexicano-rodriguez-y-es-nuevo-campeon-mundial-paja-de-la-fib,1ed5a7af252bd310VgnCLD2000000ec6eb0aRCRD.html|title=Japonés Takayama vence a mexicano Rodríguez y es nuevo campeón mundial paja de la FIB|publisher=[[Terra Networks|Terra Chile]]|date=March 30, 2013|accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref> He was the first foreign boxer for ALA Promotions, and became the third ever world champion for them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sunstar.com.ph/cebu/sports/2013/04/02/takayama-gives-ala-third-world-title-275497|title=Takayama gives ALA third world title|author=Edri K. Aznar|date=April 2, 2013|publisher=''Sun.Star Cebu''|accessdate=April 3, 2013}}</ref> "I'm gonna float like a butterfly and sting like a bee," Takayama had told at the pre-fight conference.<ref group="Video">{{Cite video|date=March 27, 2013|title=IBFミニフライ級記者会見|url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=V6J3NdRBlog#t=4m24.2s|time=4:24|medium=[[YouTube]] video|language=Spanish/Japanese|publisher=Osaka Tenjin Gym|accessdate=April 3, 2013}}</ref> He tried to imitate the [[Muhammad Ali|Ali shuffle]] during the fight.<ref group="Video">{{Cite video|date=November 28, 2011|title=Despojan del título al Dragoncito Rodríguez|url=http://televisadeportes.esmas.com/video/noticias/214564/despojan-del-titulo-al-dragoncito-rodriguez/|language=Spanish|publisher=[[Televisa Deportes Network|TelevisaDeportes.com]]|accessdate=April 3, 2013}}</ref>

===Triumphant return to Japan===
The JBC joined the WBO and the IBF on April 1, 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Joe Koizumi|url=http://www.fightnews.com/Boxing/japan-joins-ibf-180585|title=Japan joins IBF|date=March 22, 2013|publisher=Fightnews.com|accessdate=June 5, 2013}}</ref> After more than four years' absence from the ring in Japan, Takayama's boxer's license was issued again by the JBC on July 12, 2013. He registered with Nakazato-Atsumi Boxing Gym and will fight in Japan in around September.<ref>{{Cite news|title=IBF王者高山にJBCライセンス再発行|url=http://www.nikkansports.com/battle/news/f-bt-tp0-20130712-1156339.html|publisher=''Nikkan Sports''|date=July 12, 2013|accessdate=July 12, 2013|language=Japanese}}</ref>

